April 12 - Issue #118


On Wednesday afternoon, midway through his grilling at the hands of the Hou=
se of Representatives, Mark Zuckerberg was asked about Facebook's data coll=
ection practices. The company develops profiles for people who have never u=
sed the service. Why? &quot;In general we collect data on people who are no=
t signed up for Facebook for security purposes,&quot; Zuckerberg responded.=
=C2=A0

The Journal's Deepa Seetharaman tweeted the questions (https://twitter.com/=
dseetharaman/status/984112968328712192) that immediately came to mind: &quo=
t;What security purposes? How else is that data used? Do those users know t=
hat Facebook has the info and can they delete it?&quot; I predicted (https:=
//twitter.com/CaseyNewton/status/984113071672115201) the tech press would f=
ocus on this point over the next day. It largely did, and I'm grateful for =
everyone who worked to illuminate the issue.

The basic idea goes like this: there is the data that you volunteer to Face=
book, and there is the data that Facebook collects about you regardless. Du=
ring the hearings, lawmakers focused largely =E2=80=94 if not exclusively =
=E2=80=94 on the former category. But by the the end of Wednesday's harder-=
edged hearing, it became clear that the latter category was not nearly as w=
ell understood. And given its secretive nature, it's worth much more scruti=
ny.

As Ben Thompson put it today (https://stratechery.com/2018/zuckerbergs-hous=
e-hearing-toutiaos-apology-apples-siri-hire/):=C2=A0

&quot;Nearly every time questioning touched on privacy, Zuckerberg immediat=
ely emphasized that Facebook gives users tools to control who sees their da=
ta. It was a quite clever =E2=80=94 and effective =E2=80=94 sleight of hand=
: the questions were about the data Facebook owns about each user, but Zuck=
erberg=E2=80=99s answers were about content you upload to Facebook.&quot;We=
 introduced this issue in yesterday's newsletter (https://www.getrevue.co/p=
rofile/caseynewton/issues/the-house-strikes-back-at-facebook-106626), amid =
the discussion of Congress' pressure on Facebook to explain how it tracks u=
sers around the web. But let's drill down a bit further.

The story begins with Rep. Joe Kennedy, who pushed Zuckerberg into acknowle=
dging (https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-11/zuckerberg-says-f=
acebook-collects-internet-data-on-non-users) the existence of what are comm=
only called &quot;shadow profiles.&quot;=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t unde=
rstand how users then own that data,=E2=80=9D Kennedy said. In the Atlantic=
, Alexis Madrigal called it the most important exchange of the hearing (htt=
ps://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/04/the-most-important-exch=
ange-of-the-zuckerberg-hearing/557795/) =E2=80=94 largely because Zuckerber=
g's answer dodged the question.

This apparent contradiction relies on the company=E2=80=99s distinction bet=
ween the content someone has intentionally shared=E2=80=94which Facebook mi=
nes for valuable targeting information=E2=80=94and the data that Facebook q=
uietly collects around the web, gathers from physical locations, and infers=
 about users based on people who have a similar digital profile. As the jou=
rnalist Rob Horning put it (https://twitter.com/robhorning/status/984122371=
891134464), that second set of data is something of a =E2=80=9Cproduct=E2=
=80=9D that Facebook makes, a =E2=80=9Csynthetic=E2=80=9D mix of actual dat=
a gathered, data purchased from outsiders, and data inferred by machine int=
elligence.With Facebook, the concept of owning your data begins to verge on=
 meaningless if it doesn=E2=80=99t include that second, more holistic conce=
pt: not just the data users create and upload explicitly, but all the other=
 information that has become attached to their profiles by other means.Ther=
e are at least three known reasons Facebook collects data about you without=
 your informed consent.=C2=A0

1. Security. If you don't have a Facebook account, or do but haven't logged=
 in, Facebook will track what you do on its public pages. Zuckerberg justif=
ied this as a security measure =E2=80=94 if it did not do this, people woul=
d be able to scrape the contents of every public Facebook page, he told law=
makers. There are likely other security reasons for collecting this kind of=
 data, but Zuckerberg didn't mention them.

2. Advertising. Yesterday we talked about the Facebook pixel (https://www.b=
uzzfeed.com/alexkantrowitz/heres-how-facebook-tracks-you-when-youre-not-on-=
facebook?utm_campaign=3DRevue%20newsletter&amp;amp;utm_medium=3DNewsletter&=
amp;amp;utm_source=3DThe%20Interface&amp;amp;utm_term=3D.xovwWDwkd#.rfw1vo1=
qd), a piece of code that advertisers use to record your web history and re=
port it back to Facebook. You can opt out of being tracked on Facebook this=
 way in your Facebook settings =E2=80=94 assuming you have a Facebook accou=
nt. If you don't, your options are unclear, at least to me.=C2=A0

3. Growth. Former Facebook ad employee Antonio Garc=C3=ADa Mart=C3=ADnez=C2=
=A0pointed out (https://twitter.com/antoniogm/status/984125752860753920) th=
at Facebook builds shadow profiles so that when you create an account, it k=
nows just who your friends are, and recommend them on your first login. Qui=
ckly connecting you to your friends and family means you will spend more ti=
me on Facebook.=C2=A0

If you don't have a Facebook account, you don't have control over this data=
: your friends gave it away on your behalf when they agreed to upload their=
 contacts to Facebook =E2=80=94 often thanks to (https://medium.com/@scf4/a=
n-example-of-a-dark-pattern-in-facebook-messenger-4211772e744f) deliberatel=
y confusing interfaces (https://twitter.com/ow/status/982227996265205764). =
You'll only find it when you join Facebook and find that it already underst=
ands your entire social graph.

It's a relevant point because the entire Cambridge Analytica scandal comes =
down to who decides how our data is used. Zuckerberg testified this week th=
at we should have control over the data Facebook collects about us. But the=
 most salient point that emerged from his testimony was that, in fact, we d=
on't.

Congress was listening. Today a bipartisan group of senators led by Amy Klo=
buchar (D-MN) and John Kennedy (R-LA) announced they would introduce new le=
gislation designed to protect consumers' data privacy (https://www.klobucha=
r.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/news-releases?ID=3DE3ABA75F-685D-498F-97D2-A6=
3EB0000E79). Among other things, the bill would &quot;ensure users have the=
 ability to see what information about them has already been collected and =
shared.&quot; And if there's one lesson that emerged from Facebook's trip t=
o Washington, it's that we don't know the half of it.


