r: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">put it</a>, that second set of data is someth=
ing of a =E2=80=9Cproduct=E2=80=9D that Facebook makes, a =E2=80=9Csyntheti=
c=E2=80=9D mix of actual data gathered, data purchased from outsiders, and =
data inferred by machine intelligence.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0; displa=
y: block; Margin: 0; Margin-bottom: 14px; padding: 0 20px; border-color: #E=
0E4E8; border-left: 2px solid #E0E4E8; color: #7A889A; line-height: inherit=
;" class=3D"revue-blockquote">With Facebook, the concept of owning your dat=
a begins to verge on meaningless if it doesn=E2=80=99t include that second,=
 more holistic concept: not just the data users create and upload explicitl=
y, but all the other information that has become attached to their profiles=
 by other means.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">There are=
 at least three known reasons Facebook collects data about you without your=
 informed consent.=C2=A0</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>1. Security</b>. If you don=E2=80=99t have a Facebook account, or do but=
 haven=E2=80=99t logged in, Facebook will track what you do on its public p=
ages. Zuckerberg justified this as a security measure =E2=80=94 if it did n=
ot do this, people would be able to scrape the contents of every public Fac=
ebook page, he told lawmakers. There are likely other security reasons for =
collecting this kind of data, but Zuckerberg didn=E2=80=99t mention them.</=
div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>2. Advertising</b>. Yesterday we talked about the <a href=3D"http://em.g=
etrevue.co/mpss/c/DAE/1EoYAA/t.2gl/Ud2-rwTIQ46KsmIQW7QVCA/h9/i4v64T3hGi-2Bt=
S5O-2Fcvz-2F5FhM-2FeIXuV1h6FsxQ68zpBdeBNjiZ8pJqQov-2FLlCEo6BDQYVw3eS9QaMRGP=
fWJT5vwF0C9dniKyCQIjo5v-2Bbtga8trlQgyjzq5fCUuLNOVY0lFX85FzZIWh0X2B1bR3p1LBh=
zyzzNgIJnw3xN0L0oaNBl6tqS41W-2BM5PiCBEay-2F5-2BSjn-2BzsMea-2F2BLufSezmE1MPK=
1spXHfKJFMOypQOC0RgDFdH-2B0BhT-2BPeqPWMTp5Vr1L4-2FtI46Q-2B7WigTK76WKA-3D-3D=
" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">Facebook pixel</a>, a piece of=
 code that advertisers use to record your web history and report it back to=
 Facebook. You can opt out of being tracked on Facebook this way in your Fa=
cebook settings =E2=80=94 assuming you have a Facebook account. If you don=
=E2=80=99t, your options are unclear, at least to me.=C2=A0</div><div style=
=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>3. Growth</b>. Former Facebook ad employee Antonio Garc=C3=ADa Mart=C3=
=ADnez=C2=A0<a href=3D"http://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c/DAE/1EoYAA/t.2gl/Ud2-rw=
